Distribution: Southern coast of India ( Pillai, 1954 , 1964 ;
Aneesh et al . 2016
, present study), Andaman Islands (
Praveenraj et al . 2017
) and Thailand ( Williams & Bunkley-Williams 1994 ).

Since records of
R. circularis
from the Indian sub–continent were made possible due to the collection of its fish host for subsistence and commercial use by local fisherman, it was an opportunity not to be missed to re-describe the species. Other reports that have further aided the ecological knowledge of the parasite include feeding behaviour (
Rameshkumar et al . 2013
), molecular identification (
Praveenraj et al . 2017
) and prevalence, mean intensity and abundance (
Aneesh et al . 2016
). We hope clarity of its taxonomy and ecology (particularly hostspecificity) creates awareness on parasitic cymothoids and their potential harm towards the aquaculture and fisheries industry should an outbreak occur.
